\b 2. Construction of the administrative limits\

\b0 \
There are overall 722 polygons in the shapefile. 719 polygons correspond to a 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gation
\i0 , and 13 correspond to areas laying within today frontiers but not being part of the French territory around 1786.\
\
Among the 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gation 
\i0 polygons, quite a few required an adjustment before being coded :\
\
		a/ The exact administrative limits of the 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  of Belac, Limoges, and Roye are not perfectly known. I follow the drawings made by the authors.\
		\
		b/ The 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  of Landau and Wissemboug shared parts of an undivided territory. I attributed it to the 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gation
\i0  of Landau.\
\
		c/ Some 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  had two capital cities at the same time. I attributed randomly the status of capital to one of these cities:\
				1/ Limoux - Alet -->  Limoux\
				2/ Orgelet - Lons-le-Saunier --> Lons-le-Saunier\
				3/ Arbois - Poligny -->  Poligny\
				4/ Quingey - Salins --> Salins\
\
		d/ Some cities (insee code in brackets) are the head office of two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations.\

\i0 				1/ Rennes (35238): the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are within the same 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9 
\i0 (Rennes). I named the first polygon 
\i Rennes I
\i0  and the second polygon 
\i Rennes II
\i0 .\
				2/ Bayonne (64102): the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are within the same 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9 
\i0 (Bordeaux).  I named the first polygon 
\i Bayonne (Lannes)
\i0  and the second polygon 
\i Bayonne (Labourd)
\i0 . \
				3/ Auxerre (89024): the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are in two different 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s
\i0  (Dijon and Paris). I named them after the 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s 
\i0 to which they belong: 
\i Auxerre (Dijon)
\i0  and 
\i Auxerre (Paris).
\i0 \
				4/ La-Souterraine (23176): the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are in two different 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s
\i0  (Limoges and Bourges). I named them after the 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s 
\i0 to which they belong: 
\i La-Souterraine (Bourges)
\i0   and 
\i La-Souterraine (Limoges)
\i0 .\
				5/ Bort (19028) : the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are in two different 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s
\i0  (Limoges and Riom). I named them after the 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s 
\i0 to which they belong: 
\i Bort (Riom)
\i0  and 
\i Bort (Limoges)
\i0 . \
				6/ Montauban (82121): the two 
\i subd\'e9l\'e9gations
\i0  are in two different 
\i G\'e9n\'e9ralit\'e9s
\i0  (Montauban and Toulouse). I named them after their historical name: 
\i Montauban
\i0  and 
\i Montauban (Bas-Montauban)\

\i0 				7/ M\'e9zi\'e8res and Charleville (08105) are nowadays the same city, and therefore share the same insee code (64102)\
\
\
N.B.: For polygons laying within today frontiers but not belonging to the French territory in 1789, I coded them using the same strategy as the other polygons. I simply coded 0 for the variable 
\i Generalite.\
